The paper presents a novel approach for object counting in images using a Mask RCNN-based architecture and a similarity-based head branch. The approach is evaluated on counting benchmarks and can also be applied to other image understanding tasks. Given this, the most likely sub-category is computer vision (cs.CV). The paper also involves machine learning techniques such as clustering and triplet loss, which suggests that it could also belong to sub-categories such as artificial intelligence (cs.AI), machine learning (cs.LG), and neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE). Finally, the paper involves similarity-based embeddings, which could also place it in the information retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category.
